          "text": "your dream = 你的夢想\nExample: Your dream deserves bravery, yes — but it also deserves discipline.\n（你的夢想值得勇氣，沒錯——但它也值得紀律。）\nAnalysis: The writer treats the dream respectfully while insisting on preparation.\n\nsurrender of your dream = 放棄夢想\nExample: Treat it not as a surrender of your dream.\n（不要把它視為放棄夢想。）\nAnalysis: This phrase recognises Kam Chai’s fear that accepting the job means betrayal.\n\ntowards it = 朝著它前進\nExample: A strategic bridge towards it.\n（一座通往它的策略性橋樑。）\nAnalysis: “It” refers to the café dream. The phrase suggests gradual progress.\n\ndreams can become dusty = 夢想會蒙塵\nExample: Dreams can become dusty if they are postponed forever.\n（如果夢想被永遠推遲，它們會蒙塵。）\nAnalysis: This phrase acknowledges the danger of over-waiting.\n\nthe dream becomes a dinner story = 夢想變成飯桌故事\nExample: The dream becomes a dinner story.\n（夢想變成飯桌上的故事。）\nAnalysis: This is a warning: an unacted dream can become something people only talk about.\n\nbravery = 勇氣\nExample: Your dream deserves bravery.\n（你的夢想值得勇氣。）\nAnalysis: The writer does not promote cowardice or comfort.\n\ndiscipline = 紀律；自律\nExample: Your dream deserves discipline.\n（你的夢想值得紀律。）\nAnalysis: This is the final moral idea of the essay.\n\nbrew it slowly = 慢慢沖泡它\nExample: Brew it slowly.\n（慢慢沖泡它。）\nAnalysis: This extends the café metaphor to mean “develop the dream patiently.”\n\nserve it well = 好好端上它；好好實現它\nExample: When the time comes, serve it well.\n（當時機來到時，好好把它端上。）\nAnalysis: This gives the conclusion emotional closure and thematic unity."
