          "text": "First = 首先\nExample: First, a café is a business before it is a romance.\n（首先，咖啡店是一門生意，其次才是浪漫。）\nUse: Introduces the first main reason.\n\nSecond = 第二\nExample: Second, the promotion may give you skills that a young café owner badly needs.\n（第二，晉升可能給你一個年輕咖啡店老闆非常需要的技能。）\nUse: Introduces the second main reason.\n\nFor example = 例如\nExample: For example, set a target.\n（例如，設定一個目標。）\nUse: Introduces practical details.\n\nBetter still = 更好的是\nExample: Better still, test the concept through weekend pop-ups.\n（更好的是，透過週末快閃店測試概念。）\nUse: Adds a stronger or more practical suggestion.\n\nIn practical terms = 實際而言\nExample: In practical terms, staying now protects your future freedom.\n（實際而言，現在留下來是在保護你未來的自由。）\nUse: Summarises the practical implication of the argument.\n\nMeanwhile = 同時\nExample: Meanwhile, the higher salary can fund your café.\n（同時，較高薪水可以資助你的咖啡店。）\nUse: Shows simultaneous benefit.\n\nGranted = 誠然；固然\nExample: Granted, your friends may say, “Why wait?”\n（誠然，你的朋友可能會說：「為甚麼要等？」）\nUse: Introduces a concession.\n\nThey have a point = 他們有道理\nExample: They have a point.\n（他們有道理。）\nUse: Acknowledges the opposing view fairly.\n\nBe that as it may = 即便如此；話雖如此\nExample: Be that as it may, the solution is not reckless resignation.\n（即便如此，解決方法不是魯莽辭職。）\nUse: Moves from concession back to the writer’s main position.\n\nDo not say vaguely = 不要含糊地說\nExample: Do not say vaguely, “I’ll wait a few years.”\n（不要含糊地說：「我會等幾年。」）\nUse: Rejects weak planning.\n\nIf the evidence is weak = 如果證據不足\nExample: If the evidence is weak, revise the plan.\n（如果證據不足，就修改計劃。）\nUse: Establishes an evidence-based decision rule.\n\ninstead of = 而不是\nExample: Revise the plan instead of gambling your future on wishful thinking.\n（修改計劃，而不是把未來押在一廂情願上。）\nUse: Shows a contrast between sensible and reckless action.\n\nAt the end of the day = 歸根究底；到頭來\nExample: At the end of the day, the best entrepreneurs are not those who leap blindly.\n（歸根究底，最好的創業者不是那些盲目跳躍的人。）\nUse: Introduces the final wisdom or conclusion."
